{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d52823b7-5cc4-4cf8-b906-44a8c1f5c7ef","content":"The standard approach is to **abstract file I/O behind an interface** and inject it:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nThen inject `IFileSystem` into your classes instead of calling `System.IO` directly. In production, wire up a thin implementation that delegates to the real `File`/`Directory` methods. In tests, use a mock or an in-memory fake.\n\n**Even easier** — use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package. It provides `IFileSystem` out of the box plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # for tests\n```\n\n```csharp\n// Production code\npublic class MyService(IFileSystem fs)\n{\n    public string Load(string path) => fs.File.ReadAllText(path);\n}\n\n// Test\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>\n{\n    { \"/data/config.json\", new MockFileData(\"{ }\") }\n});\nvar svc = new MyService(fs);\nAssert.Equal(\"{ }\", svc.Load(\"/data/config.json\"));\n```\n\nThis avoids rolling your own abstraction and covers the entire `System.IO` surface.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b37bf0ea-fac4-42ad-bf2c-1ef48bf7a983","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. This is a general software engineering question about testability patterns, not a codebase-specific task. I can answer this directly from knowledge.","outputTokens":417,"requestId":"E3DA:45E9C:21F233C:259947D:6A05360E"},"id":"92cc4435-3b5e-431c-af3c-5ebe6334bf83","timestamp":"2026-05-14T02:40:24.467Z","parentId":"ffb80ca0-0b4e-4d96-be57-7683f5a5180e"}
